docs.abstract: Amazon doesn’t have a plan to fix health care, but it loves that we’re talking about it. Facebook has a plan to fix the social network, but people may spend less time on it.

docs.lead_paragraph: Each Friday, Farhad Manjoo, The Times’s technology columnist, reviews the week’s news, offering analysis (and maybe a joke or two) about the most important developments in the tech industry. Want this newsletter in your inbox? Sign up here.

headline.main: Farhad’s Week in Tech: Less Time on Facebook, More Noise From Amazon

docs.abstract: Who smokes marijuana anymore? Because of more sophisticated marketing, people can now vape it, eat it, drink it and apply it, leading to an explosion in sales.
docs.snippet: Who smokes marijuana anymore? Because of more sophisticated marketing, people can now vape it, eat it, drink it and apply it, leading to an explosion in sales.
docs.lead_paragraph: The streets of San Francisco have always smelled of marijuana. Yet it’s worth noting that the city doesn’t seem to have gotten much smellier in the new year, after the recreational use of marijuana became legal in California under a law approved by voters in 2016.

headline.main: About That Joint: Marijuana Start-Ups Pass
headline.print_headline: I’m Good: Pot Start-Ups Pass Up the Joint

docs.abstract: Facebook faces complex questions over its prioritization of “meaningful” content in the News Feed, including whether people want that kind of content in the first place.

docs.lead_paragraph: Imagine you’re a cookie mogul. You figured out a way to make lots of money by giving away delicious cookies for free, and in less than a decade, you created a global cookie behemoth.

headline.main: The Difficulties With Facebook’s News Feed Overhaul

docs.abstract: Uber’s autonomous trucks have started hauling trailers on Arizona highways for customers for its freight-booking service.
docs.snippet: Uber’s autonomous trucks have started hauling trailers on Arizona highways for customers for its freight-booking service.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — More than a year after Uber’s self-driving trucks made their first commercial delivery — 2,000 cases of Budweiser beer on a 120-mile hop in Colorado — the company says it has taken its robot big rigs to the highways of Arizona.

headline.main: Uber’s Self-Driving Trucks Hit the Highway, but Not Local Roads
headline.print_headline: Self-Driving Trucks Hit Highway, but the Last Mile Is More Complex

docs.abstract: A woman in Tempe, Ariz., died after being hit by a self-driving car operated by Uber, in what is believed to be the first fatality of a pedestrian from an autonomous vehicle on public roads.
docs.snippet: A woman in Tempe, Ariz., died after being hit by a self-driving car operated by Uber, in what is believed to be the first fatality of a pedestrian from an autonomous vehicle on public roads.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Arizona officials saw opportunity when Uber and other companies began testing driverless cars a few years ago. Promising to keep oversight light, they invited the companies to test their robotic vehicles on the state’s roads.

headline.main: Self-Driving Uber Car Kills Pedestrian in Arizona, Where Robots Roam
headline.print_headline: Woman’s Death in Arizona Casts A Pall on Driverless Car Testing

docs.abstract: Less than four weeks after President Trump signed a new tax bill, Apple plans to repatriate the vast majority of its $252 billion in cash held abroad.
docs.snippet: Less than four weeks after President Trump signed a new tax bill, Apple plans to repatriate the vast majority of its $252 billion in cash held abroad.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Apple, which had long deferred paying taxes on its foreign earnings and had become synonymous with hoarding money overseas, unveiled plans on Wednesday that would bring back the vast majority of the $252 billion in cash that it held abroad and said it would make a sizable investment in the United States.

headline.main: Apple, Capitalizing on New Tax Law, Plans to Bring Billions in Cash Back to U.S.
headline.print_headline: Apple, After Tax Cut Windfall, Will Bring Billions Back to U.S.

byline.original: By Daisuke Wakabayashi and Brian X. Chen
